comparisons.base_model_summary:
The Floyd are described as "wasting away". They were described as "a bunch of morons" by critics. It was suggested that the group may have been formed in a prison. In an interview with the Irish magazine "Munster", the band said they had left the group "after having just been released from prison" because of "psychological problems".

The first recording session took place between January and July 1975 at the Abbey Road Studios in London. It was later recorded at the studios in Birmingham, which were owned by Harvest Records and Columbia Records. This is the first time that the group has worked with two major record companies - Harvest and EMI. The album's production was handled by Peter Gabriel, who also produced other Pink Floyd records, including "Achtung Baby" and "We Will Rock You". He was asked to produce the song "Have a Cigar" for the album. The lead singer Roy Harper was invited to take part in the recording process.
